Of course, this equals \(\sum_{k=1}^{\infty} \frac{{k}}{{2}^{k}}\).
Now recalling the sum of infinite geometric series,
\begin{align*}
\sum_{k=0}^{\infty} r^{k} = \frac{1}{1 - r}, \quad |r| < 1,
\end{align*}
and differentiating both sides with respect to \(r\), we get
\begin{align*}
\sum_{k=1}^{\infty} k{r}^{k-1} = \frac{1}{(1 - r)^2}.
\end{align*}
So now plugging in \(r = \tfrac{1}{2}\), we have in particular
\begin{align*}
\sum_{k=1}^{\infty} \frac{{k}}{{2}^{k}} = \frac{1 / 2}{(1 - 1/2)^2} = \boxed{2}.
\end{align*} </think> <answer>2</answer>

